of how systems were built

495
00:21:41,800 --> 00:21:43,467
and what they were built for,

496
00:21:43,567 --> 00:21:46,867
that plays out, continues
to play out even to this day,

497
00:21:46,967 --> 00:21:48,367
a hundred-plus years later,

498
00:21:48,467 --> 00:21:52,067
and that is a weight on any
person who enters the system.

499
00:21:52,133 --> 00:21:55,200
As an ex-knucklehead myself,
turned professional,

500
00:21:55,300 --> 00:21:59,300
I messed up in life,
I made some poor choices,

501
00:21:59,400 --> 00:22:03,233
but no one anywhere
in the criminal justice system

502
00:22:03,333 --> 00:22:06,133
told me that felonies
were gonna be forever.

503
00:22:06,233 --> 00:22:09,700
I've seen that the barriers
just continue,

504
00:22:09,800 --> 00:22:12,267
seen that no matter what I do

505
00:22:12,367 --> 00:22:14,867
or how much of a great effort
I put forward,

506
00:22:14,967 --> 00:22:20,267
society's still allowed to
socially acceptably mistreat me.

507
00:22:20,367 --> 00:22:23,300
- You could buy someone a house
and send them to college

508
00:22:23,400 --> 00:22:24,933
for what it costs, you know,

509
00:22:25,067 --> 00:22:26,733
at least put a down payment
on a house,

510
00:22:26,833 --> 00:22:27,933
for what it costs
to incarcerate.

511
00:22:28,067 --> 00:22:29,533
So what are we
really trying to do?

512
00:22:29,633 --> 00:22:31,600
We have the money;
why are we locking people up

513
00:22:31,700 --> 00:22:34,067
when we could use resources
or redirect them

514
00:22:34,100 --> 00:22:36,133
to really help people
out of a hole?

515
00:22:36,233 --> 00:22:41,233
- I learned in my reporting the
term 'crimeless revocations.'

516
00:22:41,333 --> 00:22:43,067
I'd love to get you to,
you know,

517
00:22:43,100 --> 00:22:46,300
let our viewers know
what it exactly means

518
00:22:46,400 --> 00:22:51,333
and how it leads and feeds
the pipeline to prison.

519
00:22:51,433 --> 00:22:53,833
- The working definition
of a crimeless revocation

520
00:22:53,933 --> 00:22:55,667
is placing a person into prison

521
00:22:55,767 --> 00:22:58,867
or placing a person
back into incarceration

522
00:22:58,967 --> 00:23:00,567
for not having
committed a new crime,

523
00:23:00,667 --> 00:23:03,967
but for a technical violation
or rules violation of some kind.

524
00:23:04,067 --> 00:23:07,133
- The way that plays out
specifically is perhaps

525
00:23:07,233 --> 00:23:09,533
you bought a car and didn't
get it cleared with your agent.

526
00:23:09,633 --> 00:23:10,933
- Alex: Yeah,
you used a computer.

527
00:23:11,067 --> 00:23:12,167
- You used a computer.

528
00:23:12,267 --> 00:23:14,500
You got married
and didn't ask for permission.

529
00:23:14,600 --> 00:23:16,567
I know that
those are some extreme things,

530
00:23:16,667 --> 00:23:18,733
but I know folks who have
feared for their lives

531
00:23:18,833 --> 00:23:21,500
or their freedom for doing
things just like that.

532
00:23:21,600 --> 00:23:22,733
But just think about this,

533
00:23:22,833 --> 00:23:24,733
the crazy numbers,
to Alex's point,

534
00:23:24,833 --> 00:23:28,267
of people in prison
are folks who have returned

535
00:23:28,367 --> 00:23:29,933
on technicalities.

536
00:23:30,067 --> 00:23:31,400
- We look at states like Oregon,

537
00:23:31,500 --> 00:23:32,600
we look at states
like Washington,

538
00:23:32,700 --> 00:23:35,633
that are putting huge dollars
into programs

539
00:23:35,733 --> 00:23:38,133
of figuring out how to get
parents things they need

540
00:23:38,233 --> 00:23:39,300
while they're locked up,

541
00:23:39,400 --> 00:23:40,700
figuring out how
to get families reunited

542
00:23:40,800 --> 00:23:42,067
while folks are locked up,

543
00:23:42,133 --> 00:23:44,233
figuring how to get families
that have somebody locked up

544
00:23:44,333 --> 00:23:45,767
the resources they need.

545
00:23:46,767 --> 00:23:49,267
And our state has a lot
of catching up to do, for sure.

546
00:23:49,367 --> 00:23:52,633
- Minnesota has a comparable
demographic to Wisconsin,

547
00:23:52,733 --> 00:23:56,133
but they don't incarcerate
nearly as much as we do.

548
00:23:56,233 --> 00:23:57,633
It really is big business.

549
00:23:57,733 --> 00:24:00,067
That's not just cliché;
it's really big business.

550
00:24:00,133 --> 00:24:04,567
- Another learning process
I went through in this reporting

551
00:24:04,667 --> 00:24:07,067
is I learned about language,
and I learned that

552
00:24:07,100 --> 00:24:09,700
I'm guilty of saying some things
that, you know,

553
00:24:09,800 --> 00:24:12,833
aren't humanizing people.

554
00:24:12,933 --> 00:24:15,700
How important is
the language of incarceration?

555
00:24:15,800 --> 00:24:21,100
- When we're talking about
felons or convicts or inmates,

556
00:24:21,200 --> 00:24:23,100
you know, last I checked,
I was a person,

557
00:24:23,200 --> 00:24:24,933
and I continue to be that.

558
00:24:25,067 --> 00:24:26,333
And so person-first language

559
00:24:26,433 --> 00:24:28,667
is something
that we've been driving on

560
00:24:28,767 --> 00:24:30,967
in this work that we do
for quite some time.

561
00:24:31,067 --> 00:24:33,933
- It's the language that
helps us to reinforce barriers.

562
00:24:34,067 --> 00:24:35,200
"This person can't be trusted,

563
00:24:35,300 --> 00:24:36,700
"I don't want you
around my family,

564
00:24:36,800 --> 00:24:39,533
you can't come to my church,
you can't work at my job,"

565
00:24:39,633 --> 00:24:42,633
so it begins
with even the language.

566
00:24:42,733 --> 00:24:44,400
And again, what it conjures
in our minds

567
00:24:44,500 --> 00:24:46,500
about what this person
is capable of,

568
00:24:46,600 --> 00:24:47,833
but when you use
those terminologies,

569
00:24:47,933 --> 00:24:50,833
you don't really think that
they're really ex or former.

570
00:24:50,933 --> 00:24:52,400
It's just you did some time,

571
00:24:52,500 --> 00:24:53,900
but you're still
in that same place,

572
00:24:54,067 --> 00:24:55,967
and that's why
we keep that same title.

573
00:24:56,067 --> 00:24:57,567
We just put ex in front of it.

574
00:24:57,667 --> 00:25:01,100
- I have employees that go
to UW who are 19 and white,

575
00:25:01,200 --> 00:25:04,100
