00:40:53,900 --> 00:40:56,967
with people like Kabby Hong,
Teacher of the Year.

985
00:40:57,067 --> 00:40:59,100
- And then, if you look
at this paragraph.

986
00:40:59,200 --> 00:41:02,700
For so many kids of color,

987
00:41:02,800 --> 00:41:03,867
they've never had

988
00:41:03,967 --> 00:41:06,233
a teacher of color.

989
00:41:06,333 --> 00:41:08,700
A lot of the university programs
are not diverse.

990
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:12,067
So if your feeder pool
of teacher applicants

991
00:41:12,100 --> 00:41:13,200
is not diverse,

992
00:41:13,300 --> 00:41:14,667
then, of course,
you're not gonna have

993
00:41:14,767 --> 00:41:16,633
a diverse
teaching workforce.

994
00:41:16,733 --> 00:41:19,800
- Seymour: In 2020, researchers
at the Wisconsin Policy Forum

995
00:41:19,900 --> 00:41:22,533
took an extensive look
into the racial diversity

996
00:41:22,633 --> 00:41:25,467
of Wisconsin teachers, and
the student-to-teacher pipeline.

997
00:41:25,567 --> 00:41:27,200
The takeaway...
- I want you to...

998
00:41:27,300 --> 00:41:29,733
- Sara: [exhaling]
We have a lot more work to do.

999
00:41:29,833 --> 00:41:31,267
- Seymour: Shaw says, ideally...

1000
00:41:31,367 --> 00:41:33,900
- That the diversity of the
student body would be reflected

1001
00:41:34,067 --> 00:41:36,600
in the diversity of
the teacher population.

1002
00:41:36,700 --> 00:41:39,167
- Seymour: While almost one
third of students in Wisconsin

1003
00:41:39,267 --> 00:41:42,433
are students of color, only
about 6% of their teachers are,

1004
00:41:42,533 --> 00:41:44,700
and many don't stay.

1005
00:41:44,800 --> 00:41:47,067
- Teachers of color who come
into the workforce are leaving

1006
00:41:47,133 --> 00:41:49,367
at a faster rate
than our white teachers.

1007
00:41:49,467 --> 00:41:50,700
- Okay?

1008
00:41:50,800 --> 00:41:52,867
- Seymour: Many educators
say a diverse teaching staff

1009
00:41:52,967 --> 00:41:55,867
positively impacts all students
in a lot of different ways.

1010
00:41:55,967 --> 00:41:58,567
- We see positive impacts
across everything

1011
00:41:58,667 --> 00:42:00,333
from student motivation

1012
00:42:00,433 --> 00:42:03,933
to strong student-teacher
relationships,

1013
00:42:04,067 --> 00:42:08,267
to absenteeism, graduation rates
and going on to college.

1014
00:42:08,367 --> 00:42:11,367
- When you look
at the educational inequities,

1015
00:42:11,467 --> 00:42:13,767
I think it is
just intrinsically tied

1016
00:42:13,867 --> 00:42:15,967
to the inequities
that are in society,

1017
00:42:16,067 --> 00:42:17,833
but it's gonna take
policy changes--

1018
00:42:17,933 --> 00:42:19,067
not just talk.

1019
00:42:19,100 --> 00:42:21,467
- For his part,
Verona Superintendent Clardy

1020
00:42:21,567 --> 00:42:24,233
is moving beyond talking
and taking action.

1021
00:42:24,333 --> 00:42:25,900
- I'm not a worrier;
I'm a doer.

1022
00:42:26,067 --> 00:42:27,933
And so we're about
doing the work.

1023
00:42:29,633 --> 00:42:30,700
- We continue our reporting

1024
00:42:30,800 --> 00:42:32,067
on race and education

1025
00:42:32,167 --> 00:42:34,200
in the state of Wisconsin
here from the campus

1026
00:42:34,300 --> 00:42:35,867
of the University of Wisconsin
in Madison.

1027
00:42:35,967 --> 00:42:37,200
Here to continue
the conversation,

1028
00:42:37,300 --> 00:42:38,800
we're joined by Dr. Alex Gee

1029
00:42:38,900 --> 00:42:41,767
from the Nehemiah Center
for Urban Leadership
and Development.

1030
00:42:41,867 --> 00:42:44,567
Mr. Kaleem Caire, Superintendent
of One City Schools

1031
00:42:44,667 --> 00:42:45,933
here in Madison,

1032
00:42:46,067 --> 00:42:48,333
and Dr. Courtney Bell,
who is the director

1033
00:42:48,433 --> 00:42:50,600
of the Wisconsin Center
for Educational Research.

1034
00:42:50,700 --> 00:42:53,700
As I've traveled and talked
to folks across the state

1035
00:42:53,800 --> 00:42:55,367
about this issue,

1036
00:42:55,467 --> 00:42:57,367
I get the sense
that it's a very touchy subject.

1037
00:42:57,467 --> 00:42:58,800
Is there something to that?

1038
00:42:58,900 --> 00:43:01,333
- Race is a touchy subject
in the United States.

1039
00:43:01,433 --> 00:43:05,267
I think, when we think
about systemic racism,

1040
00:43:05,367 --> 00:43:07,633
which exists in education,

1041
00:43:07,733 --> 00:43:10,100
we think about these sort
of interlocking layers

1042
00:43:10,200 --> 00:43:11,467
of systems and policies, right?

1043
00:43:11,567 --> 00:43:13,267
So, you only need
to think about

1044
00:43:13,367 --> 00:43:15,100
how do we draw
the district boundary,

1045
00:43:15,200 --> 00:43:17,067
and the way that interacts
with the neighborhoods,

1046
00:43:17,167 --> 00:43:20,300
the neighborhood
attendance zone,

1047
00:43:20,400 --> 00:43:23,167
the teachers
the school can attract,

1048
00:43:23,267 --> 00:43:25,633
the outcomes that then wind up
in that neighborhood,

1049
00:43:25,733 --> 00:43:27,133
that those
are interlocking systems.

1050
00:43:27,233 --> 00:43:32,100
So, it is contentious, I think
partly because people do care,

1051
00:43:32,200 --> 00:43:33,900
but the persistent inequalities
are hard to look at

1052
00:43:34,067 --> 00:43:35,233
in this state,
in particular.

1053
00:43:35,333 --> 00:43:37,433
- Dr. Gee, why are people
afraid to talk about this?

1054
00:43:37,533 --> 00:43:39,100
- Because I think
it's difficult

1055
00:43:39,200 --> 00:43:40,567
to face up to the culpability.

1056
00:43:40,667 --> 00:43:44,233
We like to quote statistics,
but we don't really want

1057
00:43:44,333 --> 00:43:46,267
to look at our ownership
in the problem

1058
00:43:46,367 --> 00:43:48,267
or why we've allowed
it to persist.

1059
00:43:48,367 --> 00:43:52,333
In educational services systems,

1060
00:43:52,433 --> 00:43:54,533
we want to fight
against racism,

1061
00:43:54,633 --> 00:43:56,633
but when we don't
properly address it,

1062
00:43:56,733 --> 00:43:58,500
the educational systems
themselves

1063
00:43:58,600 --> 00:44:00,233
become breeding grounds
for racism.

1064
00:44:00,333 --> 00:44:03,067
And I think we just like
to pass the buck

1065
00:44:03,133 --> 00:44:05,867
to someone else without
taking full responsibility.

1066
00:44:05,967 --> 00:44:08,633
- I think they're both
absolutely spot on,

1067
00:44:08,733 --> 00:44:11,433
but I also think that
we have divorced ourselves

1068
00:44:11,533 --> 00:44:13,867
from the problem.

1069
00:44:13,967 --> 00:44:17,167
That it is not only something
that I'm embarrassed

1070
00:44:17,267 --> 00:44:18,967
or don't want to be culpable in,

1071
00:44:19,067 --> 00:44:24,067
but it's been persistent
for so long,

1072
00:44:25,067 --> 00:44:27,600
and if I know about it,
I'm tired of hearing of it,

1073
00:44:27,700 --> 00:44:29,633
and so, it brings me down.

1074
00:44:29,733 --> 00:44:31,233
I've heard people say that,
like,

1075
00:44:31,333 --> 00:44:34,467
"I can't focus on the problem
'cause it just brings me down.

1076
00:44:34,567 --> 00:44:35,867
"'Cause it's like
we've not solved it,

1077
00:44:35,967 --> 00:44:37,267
it's not gonna be solved."

1078
00:44:37,367 --> 00:44:39,300
And so, I think
there's a lot of hopelessness.

1079
00:44:39,400 --> 00:44:43,067
I also think that we also
live in a state that,

1080
00:44:43,133 --> 00:44:45,467
by and large, has been
privileged for a very long time,

1081
00:44:45,567 --> 00:44:47,633
particularly in the area
where we are in Madison.

1082
00:44:47,733 --> 00:44:50,733
And so, when you're privileged,
and things are going okay,

1083
00:44:50,833 --> 00:44:53,333
and you don't have to
focus on the issue,

1084
00:44:53,433 --> 00:44:55,667
you act like it doesn't exist.

1085
00:44:55,767 --> 00:44:57,467
- But this lack of success
that we're seeing,

1086
00:44:57,567 --> 00:45:00,267
is it more to blame
on the teachers,

1087
00:45:00,367 --> 00:45:02,767
or is it more to blame
on students?

1088
00:45:02,867 --> 00:45:06,433
- I think there's enough blame
to go around, actually.

1089
00:45:06,533 --> 00:45:09,700
But I think, if we ignore
the systemic issues,

1090
00:45:09,800 --> 00:45:14,400
and only point fingers to the
parents, the students, teachers,

1091
00:45:14,500 --> 00:45:15,900
not look
at the larger issue,

1092
00:45:16,067 --> 00:45:19,233
I think we continue just
to kick the can down the road.

1093
00:45:19,333 --> 00:45:23,167
And so, I think we have to
look at really how we got here.

1094
00:45:23,267 --> 00:45:26,067
I think what makes it
even more difficult is

1095
00:45:26,100 --> 00:45:28,667
that education has been deemed
the great equalizer.

1096
00:45:28,767 --> 00:45:31,233
Education is what brings you
into the mainstream,

1097
00:45:31,333 --> 00:45:33,067
and it keeps you from being
discriminated against.

1098
00:45:33,100 --> 00:45:34,533
It keeps you from being poor.

1099
00:45:34,633 --> 00:45:36,700
And when that system
that's meant to elevate us

1100
00:45:36,800 --> 00:45:38,233
is keeping certain people down

1101
00:45:38,333 --> 00:45:40,433
it's the antithesis
to what we think

1102
00:45:40,533 --> 00:45:41,900
of when we think
about education.

1103
00:45:42,067 --> 00:45:43,300
And then,
we have to really begin

1104
00:45:43,400 --> 00:45:45,067
to ask ourselves
real tough questions.

1105
00:45:45,167 --> 00:45:46,900
But we're trying
to educate children

1106
00:45:47,067 --> 00:45:48,967
in a system, in a world,
in a reality

1107
00:45:49,067 --> 00:45:51,967
where there's
so much brokenness and pain,

1108
00:45:52,067 --> 00:45:53,600
and disregard
for who they are,

1109
00:45:53,700 --> 00:45:55,433
their pain, and their culture.

1110
00:45:55,533 --> 00:45:57,433
So, I think we really need
an overhaul

1111
00:45:57,533 --> 00:45:59,800
in how we even look at
what education means for us.

1112
00:45:59,900 --> 00:46:02,667
- And we know a lot of times
we find solutions looking

1113
00:46:02,767 --> 00:46:04,400
at other communities,
other school districts,

1114
00:46:04,500 --> 00:46:05,967
things like that.

1115
00:46:06,067 --> 00:46:10,767
Dr. Bell, we know you work
across the world, the country,

1116
00:46:10,867 --> 00:46:12,333
looking at different ways
people do research

1117
00:46:12,433 --> 00:46:14,067
to solve these kinds of issues.

1118
00:46:14,100 --> 00:46:16,333
Is there any district
out there anywhere

1119
00:46:16,433 --> 00:46:20,733
that's doing things well in
terms of addressing these issues

1120
00:46:20,833 --> 00:46:22,967
with Black and brown
students falling behind?

1121
00:46:23,067 --> 00:46:25,100
- You know there
are success cases.

1122
00:46:25,200 --> 00:46:29,333
My colleague
Gudiel R. Crosthwaite
is the superintendent

1123
00:46:29,433 --> 00:46:33,100
in Lynwood Unified,
which is in LA.

1124
00:46:33,200 --> 00:46:35,267
They have
community-based schools.

1125
00:46:35,367 --> 00:46:39,300
They have colleagues of color,
professionals of color

1126
00:46:39,400 --> 00:46:41,133
in those school buildings.

1127
00:46:41,233 --> 00:46:44,767
Not <i>only</i> colleagues of color,
but some.

1128
00:46:44,867 --> 00:46:46,567
They are committed.

1129
00:46:46,667 --> 00:46:48,633
They believe
that all those kids can learn.

1130
00:46:48,733 --> 00:46:51,067
They have tons of AP courses
in those high schools.

1131
00:46:51,100 --> 00:46:53,800
They are starting
with early Pre-K.

1132
00:46:53,900 --> 00:46:56,067
And so, they hold them tight,

1133
00:46:56,133 --> 00:46:57,767
and they treat them
with dignity,

1134
00:46:57,867 --> 00:47:00,333
and those families with
dignity the whole way up.

1135
00:47:00,433 --> 00:47:02,133
- Now Kaleem, you've built
a pretty unique environment

1136
00:47:02,233 --> 00:47:03,333
in One City.

1137
00:47:03,433 --> 00:47:05,267
What are some of the things
that you're doing

1138
00:47:05,367 --> 00:47:07,167
that you feel like
other districts can learn from?

1139
00:47:07,267 --> 00:47:08,667
- Well, there's
quite a few things.

1140
00:47:08,767 --> 00:47:11,200
First and foremost, it's
the number of our young people

1141
00:47:11,300 --> 00:47:14,733
that are coming to us who
are so far behind academically.

1142
00:47:14,833 --> 00:47:16,600
Doesn't matter
the grade level that they're at,

1143
00:47:16,700 --> 00:47:17,967
but it's even more depressing

1144
00:47:18,067 --> 00:47:21,067
when they come to you in 9th
and 10th grade and who have a...

1145
00:47:21,167 --> 00:47:23,800
We have a third of our kids
are at the--

1146
00:47:23,900 --> 00:47:26,733
somewhere between 1st and 4th
grade level in math and reading.

1147
00:47:26,833 --> 00:47:29,633
It's like you just pass them
along to 9th and 10th grade

1148
00:47:29,733 --> 00:47:32,933
without intervening to address
their real core challenges.

1149
00:47:33,067 --> 00:47:35,800
First six to eight weeks,
we get to know our kids.

1150
00:47:35,900 --> 00:47:38,067
Then we pivot
'cause we see where they're at.

1151
00:47:38,100 --> 00:47:39,667
We test 'em, we look
at what they're,

1152
00:47:39,767 --> 00:47:41,300
how they interact in school,

1153
00:47:41,400 --> 00:47:43,400
how they show up
as students every day.

1154
00:47:43,500 --> 00:47:46,333
And two hours in the morning
students are in math.

1155
00:47:46,433 --> 00:47:48,800
Two hours in the afternoon,
they're in language arts,

1156
00:47:48,900 --> 00:47:50,433
and it's not just
instruction all day.

1157
00:47:50,533 --> 00:47:52,767
The first part of that
is instruction at their level.

1158
00:47:52,867 --> 00:47:54,967
And then we bring in tutors
that we've trained.

1159
00:47:55,067 --> 00:47:57,100
We've trained
over 50 tutors to come in,

1160
00:47:57,200 --> 00:47:59,867
and work with them one-on-one,
no more than one-on-two

1161
00:48:00,067 --> 00:48:02,133
to help them
to get up to grade levels.

1162
00:48:02,233 --> 00:48:05,900
So we have a personalized
learning environment for them

1163
00:48:06,067 --> 00:48:07,400
so we can move them forward.

1164
00:48:07,500 --> 00:48:09,700
So we won't be passing
kids in our school forward

1165
00:48:09,800 --> 00:48:12,067
to 9th and 10th grade
who aren't ready to be there.

1166
00:48:12,100 --> 00:48:15,300
- Dr. Gee, you've got one
superpower I'm gonna give you

1167
00:48:15,400 --> 00:48:16,700
to fix this problem.

1168
00:48:16,800 --> 00:48:18,167
What are you gonna do with it?

1169
00:48:18,267 --> 00:48:20,467
- We've got to really embed
the importance

1170
00:48:20,567 --> 00:48:21,967
of helping students to...

1171
00:48:22,067 --> 00:48:23,833
and I'll speak specifically
to our work

1172
00:48:23,933 --> 00:48:26,833
with African American children

1173
00:48:26,933 --> 00:48:29,833
with really understanding
and appreciating the culture.

1174
00:48:29,933 --> 00:48:32,633
You know, if we were to
go back in time 60 years ago,

1175
00:48:32,733 --> 00:48:34,367
we would not be having
this conversation.

1176
00:48:34,467 --> 00:48:36,167
Black people were going to

1177
00:48:36,267 --> 00:48:38,567
historically Black
colleges and universities.

1178
00:48:38,667 --> 00:48:40,900
Building historically Black
colleges and universities,

1179
00:48:41,067 --> 00:48:43,300
building churches
and businesses,

1180
00:48:43,400 --> 00:48:46,633
highly successful educationally
with integration.

1181
00:48:46,733 --> 00:48:48,067
And one of my mentors,

1182
00:48:48,133 --> 00:48:49,633
and she probably
has mentored all of us,

1183
00:48:49,733 --> 00:48:51,067
Dr. Gloria
Ladson-Billings has always said,

1184
00:48:51,133 --> 00:48:53,067
"But, Alex, remember,
with integration,

1185
00:48:53,100 --> 00:48:55,767
30,000 Black teachers
lost their jobs

1186
00:48:55,867 --> 00:48:58,700
'cause they did not,
they were not integrated."

1187
00:48:58,800 --> 00:49:00,067
- Seymour: That's right.

1188
00:49:00,167 --> 00:49:01,467
- Black students were,
Black teachers weren't,

1189
00:49:01,567 --> 00:49:04,267
and many of them
became domestics.

1190
00:49:04,367 --> 00:49:07,067
And so, we have to understand
that this is somewhat new.

1191
00:49:07,133 --> 00:49:08,733
Because again, 60 years ago,
we weren't saying,

1192
00:49:08,833 --> 00:49:10,200
"How do we educate
our Black children?"

1193
00:49:10,300 --> 00:49:11,800
We were probably asking,
"How do we vote?"

1194
00:49:11,900 --> 00:49:13,300
But Black children
were becoming

1195
00:49:13,400 --> 00:49:15,800
dentists and doctors
and nurses and professors,

1196
00:49:15,900 --> 00:49:17,400
and then something happened.

1197
00:49:17,500 --> 00:49:20,733
So my superpower would be,
let's get them in places

1198
00:49:20,833 --> 00:49:23,067
where teachers can relate
to them, understand them,

1199
00:49:23,167 --> 00:49:27,733
celebrate them, and where they
see themselves in textbooks.

1200
00:49:27,833 --> 00:49:29,333
I came to Madison advanced
in 2nd grade,

1201
00:49:29,433 --> 00:49:31,733
but I had a Black teacher
in 1st grade who told me

1202
00:49:31,833 --> 00:49:33,733
I was gonna be the president
of the United States.

1203
00:49:33,833 --> 00:49:36,067
She's 102 years old,
and we're still pen pals.

1204
00:49:36,133 --> 00:49:38,100
We're talking is if
we have to fix Black children.

1205
00:49:38,200 --> 00:49:39,700
What we have to
really ask ourselves is,

1206
00:49:39,800 --> 00:49:41,300
"How are we
breaking Black children?"

1207
00:49:41,400 --> 00:49:44,267
- So, we know most parts
of Wisconsin

1208
00:49:44,367 --> 00:49:47,200
have a very tiny population
of students of color,

1209
00:49:47,300 --> 00:49:48,667
if any at all.

1210
00:49:48,767 --> 00:49:51,267
So when you talk about the folks
that sit at home right now,

1211
00:49:51,367 --> 00:49:53,067
and say, "This has
nothing to do with me."

1212
00:49:53,167 --> 00:49:56,933
How do we get those
folks to have a stake

1213
00:49:57,067 --> 00:49:59,067
in this game to
make things better?

1214
00:49:59,100 --> 00:50:01,400
- I'd like to go back to
something that was said earlier

1215
00:50:01,500 --> 00:50:03,367
about the function
of education in,

1216
00:50:03,467 --> 00:50:05,167
and I'll say, a democracy.

1217
00:50:05,267 --> 00:50:08,933
This affects all of us,
every single one of us,

1218
00:50:09,033 --> 00:50:10,533
no matter what
our racial background is,

1219
00:50:10,633 --> 00:50:12,067
no matter where we live.

1220
00:50:12,167 --> 00:50:13,767
If we do not have democracy,

1221
00:50:13,867 --> 00:50:15,567
that functions with civility,

1222
00:50:15,667 --> 00:50:19,133
where people can consider
issues of science

1223
00:50:19,233 --> 00:50:23,467
in the public domain of policy
around all manner of things:

1224
00:50:23,567 --> 00:50:24,933
housing, power, you name it,

1225
00:50:25,033 --> 00:50:27,567
all the things,
social services, farm subsidies,

1226
00:50:27,667 --> 00:50:28,967
whatever it may be.

1227
00:50:29,067 --> 00:50:30,700
We need an educated citizenry.

1228
00:50:30,800 --> 00:50:32,433
That's what the country
was founded on.

1229
00:50:32,533 --> 00:50:34,867
So for me,
this is about all of us.

1230
00:50:34,967 --> 00:50:38,000
These are all of our children;
this is our country.

1231
00:50:38,100 --> 00:50:39,833
- And I would say
America's at risk.

1232
00:50:39,933 --> 00:50:44,267
If you produce children
who lack an interest,

1233
00:50:44,367 --> 00:50:46,900
